{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I remember that. Ties, collars, things like that were bought at - were bought - at - Tow's, on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Sneinton Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, a haberdashery shop. Caps, things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 When were new clothes bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 When? Well when the others wore out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Some people have been telling me they were kitted out say for Whitsun or a Sunday school anniversary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Oh yes, oh aye, we - we - was always a practice of years ago that if you didn't have a - something new on 
on Palm Sunday - then the birds would mess on you. That was the - that was the saying years ago. And of course we always had something new then for Palm Sunday. It could only be a new collar or a new cap or something - like that, but it was something - so
mething new. And - you usually got, if you were having a new suit, you got it - in the springtime, so that you could have it on about Easter. Easter was the dressing up - time. And that had to last, you see.
