Yes, I went with the foster parents - two or three times - but - and this fellow that worked for them, he used to take me out as a child. He
 used to - go with him to Grimsby and such places like that to visit - his relations and so on. Me grandfather - he - an me dad's side, he used to take me out - round these small villages, Trent Lock and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you walk there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh mostly walking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember anything special on Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Apart from the time that me grandfather'd take me, he might take me to Trent Lock or somewhere like that, I mean there was - it was very little. There was very - little change, one - one period of a year to another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember Goose Fair in these days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was there anything special to say about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, on the Saturday, yes, me own father used to take us, that was something unusual. He'd take us there and -
 probably have a go at the coconuts and things like that you know, and he thought that was a part of his duty I suppose, I think it was taken more as a duty than a - an enjoyment, but - that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was it you who was telling me there really were tickling sticks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Yes. Oh yes, well - oh no, no, they were - twisted wire, with a - hair at the end you know - usually - like - hair on a - a soft broom, and these of course were sold and - only a few coppers. But the fun of it was that - the roundabouts
 were placed - closer together which made the crowds - more congested, you see, and then you'd go along, there'd be tickling one another under the chin with these - sticks you know, anything for - to start - a lark or something like that you know, it was 
a
ll - pure fun, there was none of this - nastiness about things as - you get today. It was all pure fun, I mean - if you went up - you see you'd only get this at the fair time you know. And then - probably someone'd start off - now what would they call thi
s, where you go in a - like a snake all round - they do it today sometimes. They - they catch hold of one another you know and they'd gradually weave their way - through the crowd.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 And you could catch hold of a stranger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Anyone. Anyone, and nobo
dy both - nobody bothered. The feelings today then were - then I should say were - better than what they are today. I should say so. I - we never met in my lifetime anyway, I never met anyone that objected. Mind you you - you wouldn't do it to a - a maide
n aunt or something like that, you used to - pick them - it was mostly the younger section to - they were - nobody objected.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. I used to go to a farm, on the school holiday. For the whole month.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How was this arranged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Through the foster parents. They knew them on the farm, they were friends you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So you went on your own did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Yes, I had to go by train, on my own. And - these farm people'd meet me at the station at the other
 end with a cart you see, farm cart. Then take me up to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid25946\charrsid6829132 farm and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 then - during that month's stay I used to join in with the general farm work and so on and - sometimes of an evening we'd - one of their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid25946\charrsid6829132 young sons}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  would - about me own age - we'd perhaps go into the village, or have a walk round or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Where was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Tignall, in Derbyshire. Yes, it was very nice. I enjoyed it really. And then again at Christmas time. I've been there at Christmas. Where - we used to have the ol
d fashioned - Christmas there you know where - the - neighbours from the varying farms'd come round and they'd sing the carols and then they'd have a - drink of beer and homemade pork pies and so on and then - they'd - go on to the next farm and so on. Al
l round the district. It was quite nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 If you went there Christmas did your foster parents go too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No, I just - always on me own.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So you were part of that family too almost were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, yes, at those holiday times, yes. They were very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Can you tell me how you spent Saturdays in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well, up to - early school days of course - you'd be - sweeping yards, neighbours yards, cleaning windows for a - an odd ha'penny or a penny or - if you got - tuppence for a 
- very big yard well you'd probably - you'd think you'd got a fortune. But it was mostly like that or taking the dog out or things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you help in the garden a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not a lot. No. No. Not a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How about Sundays, how did you spend Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Sundays - after breakfast it was church. From church - which we used to come out about twelve at dinnertime you know - we should probably take a slow walk home which wasn't too far, and - talk to pals in the yard until dinner time. After 
dinner it'd be Sunday school. And - you come out of Sunday school probably about half past two. And then you'd - you'd go a walk. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you go anywhere special usually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, there was - there was a good walk we used to have - down Sneinton D
ale - through Baker's field as it was called then, they had a pond in there you know where we used to go and play - fish for tiddlers. And then on - over the top of the brick yard down into Subble's spinney, and come out on what is now known is the the Co
lwick - Low Road, and come home by - the entrance to Colwick Park, and along Colwick Road and home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 It must be a bit different now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, we used to walk miles you see, we never used to think about riding because there was nothing to ride on, e
xcept trams. And - for the small amount of money you got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid25946\charrsid6829132 ha'pennies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 and pennies, of course naturally as a child you spend them on sweets and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid25946\charrsid6829132 ice cream}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 After your walk what did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh well then there'd be church again at night. You see. Well
 that'd be on 'til eight o'clock probably. And then you - you just come home, it was getting towards bedtime then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You did say you had different clothes for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 For Sunday, yes, you'd have a Sunday suit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you play games on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your parents or foster parents think it wrong to work or play on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your parents attend a place of worship or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What denomination was it you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Church of England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were there any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. They were mostly - we had - these open landaus you know, those days. And - we'd go as far as {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Woollerton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And - there we should - have sports, races, so on you know for little 
bits of prizes provided by the church. And then there'd be a tea, of a sort. Which was a good tea to us those days of course. In the riding school, at Woollerton Park.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 It's nice there isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. But - then of course - when I joined the choir there was a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid25946\charrsid6829132 holiday}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  holiday - choir outing.. They used to go to Skegness or somewhere like that, Mabletho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid25946\charrsid6829132 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 pe which was a - considered a great treat those days you see. They used to get a reserved carriage for us and - the - it'd be the - vicar, curate
, Sunday school superintendant, probably a Sunday school teacher or something like that, and just the choirboys would go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 When did you join the choir, do you remember how old you were, were you a very little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I should be about - let me see - nine, between nine and ten.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So you really had a good do when you were in the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, I was a solo voice in that church for about a couple of years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were there any other social activities organised by the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well there wa
s the ord - ordinary annual bazaar. That was held in the Sneinton - Institutes, Church Institute. And - I don't remember anything else, special, run by that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Sort of evening socials or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not as I can remember, 'cos - as childre
n we - we wouldn't be allowed in them in any case. At this bazaar we should help - you know, by - taking things over from the vicarage into the - Institute and - generally helping round as - children would you know, serving the refreshments and things lik
e that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did the church run any temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not as I noticed. They made an effort at one time - to start a - a Boy Scouts, but it never reached - much at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you belong to any other club organised by the church or chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not 
by the church. I belonged to Dakin Street Boy's Brigade. These were - at the age of about - nine I should think. But - I never - had a uniform, because - I was allowed to be in the Boys Brigade, and the religious training that they were very keen on those
 days, I got it through the church, and being in the church choir do you see, I was allowed to belong the - the Brigade without buying the uniform.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were many of you in that position?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 That I wouldn't say. I shouldn't think there was many.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not particularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your real father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you know what his views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Your father didn't take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about your real mother and your foster mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, they weren't bothered wither. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember of the four voting in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh they - 19 - yes - probably they would vote. But I - was not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid25946\charrsid6829132 keenly}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  interested in what they were doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you know what party they would have voted for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I really couldn't say. There was never any - discussion or - talk on this kind of thing at all, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So you really don't know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 But you do know something about it from Joe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Joe Corbett, yes, that was
 the man that worked - for this foster father, you see. Well he was a Labour man, strong Labour man and - he'd - talk to me on various bits of things and - about the time should I be - thirteen or fourteen years of age, I should be beginning to take an in
t
erest. Not necessarily - in line with him, but - gradually forming my own opinion, you see, and - we'd have a bit of discussion, I used to go up into the workshop you know and sit on the tailors boards, how they used to sit with their legs crossed, well I
 
used to be up there and sit on the board with him, we'd - sit hours sometimes talking and he'd bet getting on with his work - and - I should be talking to him. But - there was really nothing that I - would make me either one way or another as regards poli
tics.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you know why he was a Labour man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 That I really couldn't say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did he hold any active part in any political party or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, no. No, I should say he was keenly interested in this - Labour movement and that's all as I could say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
In some places at that time men felt they risked losing their job or their house if they voted differently from their employers. Do you know if your father or foster father or anyone felt themselves under that kind of pressure to vote for a pa
rticular party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
No. No. It never occurred - in that - in my - family life. No, never come across it, no. Not - in my family life. What happened outside my family life I really can't say, not to be accurate, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I've heard from people who lived in Arnold that those who worked at the Home Brewery or the Daybrook Laundry were under a lot of pressure.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh they would be because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not for losing their jobs but being told they ought to vote Conservative.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, yes, there's nothing about it in - in my family life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So your family didn't take much notice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - my mother was an ordinary housewife. This is the real mother? Yes. She
 was an ordinary housewife. Me father, he went to work - shall I tell you what his work was now in this section? Well he was a - a foreman - contractor for the Nottingham Corporation on the roads, a pavier, by trade. And - at those days they used to lay m
ost of the roads by these - stone blocks, called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Mount{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Sorrell{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
's. That of course was to help the horse traffic get a grip on the roads, there was no such thing much as these - asphalt roads those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Are Mount Sorrell's round cobbles or square ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
No, they - they were square with a slightly rounded top, you see - they were - stone but - most of - they called them Mount Sorrell's, whether they used to come from Mount Sorrell in Leicestershire or what I don't know, but they're a kind of a greyi
sh stone when they were laid, and they were laid - on - sand, gravel and then - the - jump - the joints were all filled in with - molten tar. You see. Well this was the system of doing most of the roads, at those - those years. Market Place, Main Road, we
re all done the same, where - the horse traffic - could get a grip, the horses hooves could get a grip in these - stones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 There are a lot of hills round here too aren't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, yes, but - that was the main - the main idea, and then gradually
 these - these Mount Sorrell's were changed over to what I believe - and I'm not quite sure about this - they called them sets, and these were a flatter type of - stone. But they'd be - shall I say like cubes about - what, seven or eight inches deep, by f
our by about three on the top, cubes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I didn't realize they were so deep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
No, they'd be about - six or seven inches deep. And these were - round into this - gravel, and then of course the heights were taken you know on the - and - then when they 
were ram - rammed in, they used to have a rammer, it was a - big piece of wood with a steel bottom, a handle halfway up and one at the top, and they used to ram them down with this, to the levels, and then the - the stones would be filled in with molten t
ar. Pitch and stuff you know. That\rquote 
s all I can tell you about those. But - as regards his life after - after he came home from work he - he - I think he used to - me own father used to spend most his time - going out at night with his pals shall we put it t
hat way, you see. He wasn't - he didn't stop much of his time at home. Not at these years. When these years, you're going up to about 1911 aren't you, 19 - or just over? Mm, yes, well he - he - he'd go out and spend his evenings with his pals. He wasn't m
uch of a home bird.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I take it he went to pubs and clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your mother have any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 None at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, she used to spend - after she'd done her daily chores and - or go out doing 
a bit of washing or things like that to bring a little bit extra money in - she'd probably - spend the whole of the evening with the girls. Then I had three sisters you see, and just spend the time at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No. She had a very poor life, we'll put it that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your real father take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not - not to my knowledge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did he attend the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did he bet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well he may have done but I don't know much about it. No. You see, I didn't live there you see. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you know if your real father or mother belonged to any savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 When your father, foster father wasn't doing his work how did he spend his time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - part of the time he sp
ent up at his garden in Mapperley. And - the remainder of the time he - he'd do the same as the other one, he'd go out and have a drink because - at those - times - they used to do a lot of their business in the pubs, you see, he'd meet - different people
 
in these pubs and they'd say, all right, Bill, will you make me a suit you see and he'd meet them in these places you see, and very often, if - it was - they're paying so much a week, you know, not on the financial schemes as there are now, but it was jus
t between themselves you see. And - they'd come in and - to the boozer and just - pay him a shilling or two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid25946\charrsid6829132 shillings}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 - whatever they could afford you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did he stick to the same boozer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh no, not - he went to several. HE WENT TO several. And 
then - some evenings in the week he'd go to - a whist drives, and they were held at these public houses you know. And he'd probably go up there perhaps one night or two nights a week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster mother go to whist drives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. She was a very homely person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did she ever go out and enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Only - once a year, they'd go out for a fortnights holiday in the mid - mid season you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 But she didn't go out in the week at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, no. Odd times on a Sunday night they ma
y go and - visit some friends in Bulwell, but that was at a public house as well. You see. And it was all done through - business. You see, he used to make the suits for this - fellow that kept the pub at - Bulwell, he made their suits for the - chap that
 kept the Donnington Arms at Castle Donnington and so on, most of his business came through those type of people. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did he belong to any clubs, were there any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, shouldn't they - I don't think, no, no - no clubs, not as I know to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster mother ever go to pubs with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Very rare. The only time she'd go would probably be of an evening she'd go - just across the road, and - just have one - drink perhaps and then come back home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster father take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
No, he was more - inclined to - be a judge - of flower shows and - and that in the - in the - in the public houses, they used to have flower shows on a Sunday dinner time as a general rule you know. Fellows would bring the flowers in from t
he gardens for a drink at Sunday dinnertime, and then they'd - he'd be one of the judges. He was a really good gardener, as had got more - in flowers and things like that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were there special flower shows?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. Well }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 you - you - there were usually chrysanthemums}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  or - beans, things like that, a few vegetables you know, and there'd be him and perhaps - another couple of people - would act as judges.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I gather in some parts of the country they have leek shows.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was it so serious in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Nottingham{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well not - the - didn't go to - now just a minute. Now when you talk about leek shows there was - there were some shows like the St Anne's - Rose Show and things like that, that were done on a very very big scale. You see. But 
I'm talking now about these that happened on a Sunday dinnertime in the public houses. They were only - organised by the publican, you see, and - he'd probably offer a little prize or something, you know, for the best. What happened to the - the produce a
fter war I don't know, I've an idea it may have gone to hospitals or - poor peopled have it I - that I really don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 St Anne's Rose Show was a very big thing was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, oh that was a big show. In fact it's running now. Yes. That used to
 be held down St Anne's Hall Road, that's was why it called St Anne's - on - now what did they call that - Donkey Hill I think they called it - it was all a piece of waste ground anyway, it was there for quite a few years and then it had various venues yo
u know, afterwards. But that was a real big - show, the same as the Chrysanthemums show, that was run on a big show, but that was properly organised by the - you know, the big shots in the business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster father attend the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was it Colwick then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did he go anywhere else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well that I don't know. But we had a fellow used to come to the house named Clark, now he was a bookmaker, he lived at Derby. And his - Clark, booking clerk was named Wyman. Now every 
- Nottingham races, they used to - go to the races, then afterwards they'd come to our house - for dinner. And a dinner was laid on for them and after dinner, the table was cleared, the clothe taken off - and - all his takings were - pushed out on the tab
le and I always remember this from the fact that - he'd say to me, now then my lad, pick all the coppers out, they're no use to us. And they were mine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How many did you get?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh well - quite a lot, yes, quite a lot. And of course I - I had to bank
 that you see, that was the starting of my - little bit of savings you see. But - they'd come every - Nottingham races. And this - same procedure, and - then odd times - as a family, the foster father and mother and myself, we'd go over to Derby and - on 
occasions during school holidays I may stay there perhaps about a week or fortnight, along with them you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster father bet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster parents belong to any savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well that I don't know beca
use they - I know me - me mother didn't, foster mother didn't, but - as regards him he was very - close as regards - what he - what money he'd got or what he did - he did with it. I wouldn't know anything about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You only had sisters didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 At the - that lived. That have lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How did you get on with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was there one you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes, the eldest one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you see them very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Yes, I used to visit me own parents. Regularly, two or three times a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 As a child who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 All the boys round about in the neighbourhood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Where did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 In the streets. In the yards. There's no such thing as - clubs those days for boys, they - ex
cept - what were run through churches and the Boys Brigades, and the Scouting associations. I mean - for a year or two I belonged Daking Street Boys Club, that was run by Oliver Hind - he was a solicitor in Nottingham, you know man with - his idea was - g
o
od intentions shall we say. Well - there, with being in the choir - I never had a uniform. Yes. I was - I was a - free from the uniform because - the religious training was got at church, but I could attend the club, and all the facilities of the club - I
 could have along with the others. But as regards - other things, playing well - we used to play in the streets.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you ever go into other peoples homes to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh - odd times, I mean, just to be - normal, not - not anything special, I mean - 
the boys across the yard, they'd come in and play with me sometimes. And - those days it was a matter of - sharing what bits of toys you did manage to get, and that was the only way we got anything different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Ah. Ah. Wel
l in - we should have - the ordinary ga - game of hopscotch, you know this - and then - we used to play cricket in the yard, 'cos it was a - a very big yard, you know, long - long yard and we could play cricket in there a bit. And - we had two - neighbour
s
 - they were - they were sisters but they were a lot older than us, but - they - liked a game with us, we used to play skipping in the yard and things like that. And then we had a game called - that - bat trap, I don't know whether you've ever come across
 
that. Well it was a - a block of wood cut out in the centre, with a bit of a lever, in - in the middle you see, and you put a ball on one end, struck the lever with the bat, and as the ball - come into the air then you knocked it you see, and you used to 
r
un - make runs then like cricket. This - yes, this bat - we used to call it bat trap, of course I expect in different districts they'd had different names for it you see. But that was a game we used to play very often and then - we had - did a bit of roll
er skating in the streets. And so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You could afford roller skates could you, or did you share them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well, as a matter of fact I had them given me, so - I - we - I couldn't have afforded to have bought a pair. But we were given them you see. Fr
iends of the family gave me the first pair, they were ordinary - cheap things, and then later on - they did give me a pair of - roller - ball bearing roller skates. And one of my - friends - his - one of his relations - was an instructor at the - Princess
 skating rink on Castle Boulevard, and - myself and him - used to go down there, out of the ordinary - hours you know, and - we were taught to - roller skate then. That was a - about as much as I can tell you. It - it was a normal boy's life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well we always got dirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you get into trouble?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
No, no - you'd - all you'd say, well you have made a mess of yourself today, and that was it, I mean it was taken as part of the - job because - the - things weren't so clean as they are today, there's no doubt about it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did either your parents or your foster parents discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, not as 
I know to, you formed your own opinion of your friends and - you just played with them. If you didn't like them well you'd fall out, you'd perhaps have a good bust up and - you'd be pals again next day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 When you were at school how did you spend your free time, did you have any hobbies then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well I don't know about hobbies. There wasn't a lot of - free time as I've told you before. Because - well we were kept pretty busy, I mean, doing little jobs about the house and one things - and another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you keep any pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I had a dog.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you collect anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - what do you mean by collect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Cigarette cards or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, oh yes, that was all the rage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Anything else like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not as I know to. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about the gardening at this stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well - I used to go up with him at night time, and - probably do a bit of bits of jobs, that I was thought capable of. And - and then - at the time when the produce was ready - we should - take up about a cou
ple of fish mats apiece, I don't know whether you've ever met these - a kind of a - a straw plaited - bag that lay - well they're very flat. Fish mats they call them. And - well that's what we call them. And - then you'd have - two of these - connected by
 a strap, and you'd have it over your shoulder and you bring down beans or apples or whichever - produce was ready you see. But - I might tell you right from Mapperley down to Sneinton was a long long walk.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 At least it was down hill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes, but it
 - but it - but he never thought - of - saying, all right, there's a ha'penny - for the - tram car. You see, the tramcars at - at those days only run up - Woodbury Road, and we had to walk - from our place on Sneinton Road - to Woodbury Road - to get on t
he tramcar, which probably made him think it wasn't - worth the while because while you was walking there you could be walking up Carlton Road, Thoneywood Lane, Porchester Road - and be at the garden you see. But it was a devil of a long way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you go fishing at this stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Mm, well if you call - fishing with a little net - fishing, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You didn't do it seriously.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not seriously. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you ever go just for walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, that was part and parcel of your life. Those da
ys. The walks - let me see now. These would occur - mostly - on Sundays. After - Sunday school. Now - one of the favourite walks was - to go down Sneinton Dale. Through the Baker's field. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Carlton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} Brickyard. And - on to what they called then Southwell Spinny. That was a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Is that where {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Southwell Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} is?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
No, that was one end of the Colwick woods. It was called Southwell Spinny because years ago - previous to this - there was a - a murder done in that wood, this fellow named Sville murdered that - 
I believe it was a young girl or something you see. But that's how it got it's name. And then we'd walk through Southwell Spinny, down to what is now known at the Colwick - Low Road, and come back by the race course - entrance to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Colwick{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Colwick Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and home. It'd be a matter of about - four - to five mile.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Any bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Yes, we'd get - go - round the district on a - cycle you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you go far on a cycle or was it a question of sharing one?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh no, I had one of
 my own, that was - given me by this - Joe Corbett. One that he'd had - years and years previously, a real old bone shaker bike, but still it was a bike, it'd go. And - no, we should - we should mostly go perhaps up as far as Bunney and - various - places
 like that. Anywhere up to about eighteen to twenty mile.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Who did you go with on these outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh any other friends that wanted to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No one special all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well apart from the school sports -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you go to any theatres at this stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not at the younger days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Now when you say theatres, now wait just the one moment. Now - if you're going to include pictures - yes, all right then. Well now I sh
ould say no then, no theatres.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Church concerts or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Except those that - well that's it, except those that were in the - church institute, things that were organised by the church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Cinemas while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Yes. Now then. This is where the fun starts. We had - tickets. Now wait a moment - the shop where I lived was a tailor's shop of course. Well now in the window we used to display these - advertisement - bills 
for these different things you see. And - there was - a picture house opened in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Shakespeare Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 called Hibberts. Well used to get a ticket - given us by - with, you know, with these - chaps that brought the bills, and that entitled you to go in for - ab
out a penny. And you'd see the whole - programme you see for a penny. Well - we'd take advantage of this and - these fellows - that brought the bills, they weren't particular about just giving you one, they'd give you a dozen, to get rid of 'em. Well we u
s
ed to dish 'em around to our friends and so on you see. Well we used to go to those pictures, and become a bit of a nuisance sometimes. Used to play - bits of tricks, like everybody else, yes. There was a fellow there that - well of course they were silen
t
 pictures of course. And - there was this fellow used to sit behind the curtain - with a - these coconut shells during these - horse - clip - clop, well we should - we should take - get - cut down reeds, open the centres take all the pith out the centre, 
and use - hawthorn hips, and - sit over in the balcony over this end and keep - pipping 'em down to him and he'd got a bald head you know and it -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Could you aim straight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, hit him plenty of times. 'Til eventually we got turned out of cour
se. And then - at this particular - picture house, they first started to synchronise a gramaphone record with the picture. And of course then we changed our seating, from the - balcony onto the front row of all. Now they had this gramaphone on a stand, an
d
 they'd start it off and it was pretty good, for a time it was pretty good. But of course - we could always stretch a hand out and just put a finger on the turn table for a second which would throw the whole thing all - haywire. That went on for a bit and
 then of course they rumbled us and we were - thrown out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I should think it was very funny wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well it was to see the picture - you know, going along and then the - all of a sudden the - the sound and the - picture - was all - distorted an
d all sorts. But it - that was a - these ware - these are the kind of tricks we used to get up to. We never did any real damage like vandalism, it were just sheer devilment. You see, and it - gradually the - these people that - that run these places, they
 got to know us and - sometimes they'd let us in and sometimes they'd just say, well now look, let's have no - bother with you lot today and that kind of thing. There was no real hardship, they didn't knock us about or anything like that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was your lot all roughly your age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did it have an actual leader or did you all sort of think these things up together
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, no, there was no leader. It was just a matter of - someone might suggest a new idea you see and - we'd - we shou
ld - try it out once and if it was a success well of course that'd carry on 'til we got stopped.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Any other things you can remember like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well we'd go to the Albert Hall on a Saturday evening and - I don't know how much we used to pay there
, I don't know whether it was a penny or tuppence, and - it'd open out - with a - the parson - saying a prayer, and we'd probably sing a hymn. Then the - picture would start. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 This was pictures too was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 This was pictures, yes, on a Saturday evening. And then of course - we should start our little bit of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 devilment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
, kicking up noises and things like that, generally trying to upset things and which we in those days thought funny, you see. And this went on for a time until the - we'd get
 thrown out of there, and - we'd go back the next week and it was all right again, but it - they - they never bore any malice or anything, they just put it down to boys - high spirits, that was all. And of course at the - interval we - we would help, you 
s
ee, as a kind of a - retribution we should - they used to sell - chocolate, and things like that, and we should - take it round on the trays and - and sell it for them, amongst the - people that were gathered - you know, went to the pictures. But - I thin
k by doing that and - trying to help what we could - part of the - time, they'd - it made up for the devilment and trouble as we were causing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you get any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Very little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was it from your real parents or from your foster parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well - my real father used to give me about threepence. The foster father gave me a ha'penny, and this - his workman gave - used to give me a ha'penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You got this regularly did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 That was regular. The rest of the pocket money you had to earn by sweeping yards or cleaning other peoples windows and - and so on.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What did you spend the money on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh mostly sweets and ice creams. 'Cos those days you see - you - you - your sweets could be bought in - farthingsworths. You see, m
ost of the sweets were four ounces a penny. You see. And - there was a shop just a little bit above us on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Sneinton Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 where you could get some jolly good ice cream and it'd only be a ha'penny what they used to call the glass. That was a scoop, stood on t
op of a glass you see, which was really good, and - we - we should - sometimes go in there and sit and - have a - ice cream and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you tell me you used to help somebody who made sweets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Can you tell me a bit about that now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well this was when I started to work half time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So you'd be how old?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Now this is what I was trying to work out. I - I should stop that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh he was a real good sport. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How do you think he treated people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well he'd - he did his duty to - where adults were concerned, and as far as our children were concerned he - he'd lash out a little bit of punishment with his little cane now and again and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 He had a cane did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, he used to carry it about, he was a police }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 sergeant}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  you see, and - this - he was really good to us, he - he took it all in good part. He probably, if he'd catch us doing any
thing wrong he'd just give us a whack with the cane and - we should feel a little bit sore and he'd just laugh at - because he'd - he - he'd managed to catch us for once, we were usually a bit too quick for him but sometimes we did get caught and that was
 it, but he was a real good sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Didn't you tell me about one time when he really did catch you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh yes, aye. Oh yes, this was a time when we go a new idea of being a bit of a nuisance. And - as boys we'd congregate on the street corner on St St
ephens Road, and there there was a shop that sold newspapers and - chocolates and various things like that, but under the window, this - to prevent condensation there were little holes drilled in the woodwork, well we should - poke a cane through there an
d
 ups all the window display you know, and this particular - evening we were do - busy doing this, and - each one of us had got a little hole apiece you know, nicely bending down and - poking, and along came this - Billie Blowett as they called him right y
o
u little devils, he says, I've just got you right where I want you, and of course we were all bending down, and the cane came across our behinds just - nice give us a right good whack apiece. Well - he laughed, we just - took it as a matt of course, we'd 
been caught and that was it. But - generally speaking he would - he would take it all as a boys lark.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 It was your lot who had the string to catch his hat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. Oh - oh this was in Manor Street, there's a lamp at - in Manor Street, and we'd - put
 a cotton, some cotton or a black string, we used to black it down with blacking and things like that so it wouldn't be so noticeable, turn out the lamp, used to climb up the lamp post you know and turn out the - gas mantle Stretch this string across the 
c
auseway and then wait for him coming you see. And then we should probably say something to start him running and he'd run after us and - helmet - would catch on the string and off it'd - pull his helmet you see. But - as I say, he took it all in good part
, he was a - he was really - as bad as us you know, for the - he took it as a laugh. We never never had any trouble with him. If he caught us well - we knew what we'd get. He - he'd - give us one with his stick. But he wouldn't be vindictive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I gather the Arnold Bobby wouldn't let children play in the streets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well that I don't know because that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 It didn't happen in your area did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 We had to play in the streets, there was nowhere else. Until - how old would I be, oh getting on I 
should think, when - there was a - a recreation ground - opened in Pennyfoot Street and there was one on Victoria - on Bath Street called the Victoria Recreation Ground but - even so the - the park keeper wouldn't allow you to play football or anything in
 it. It was very restricted, so of course we played in the streets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Bobby Blowit's name wasn't really Bobby Blow it was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh no. No, it came about - he got into a bit of a fracas - when they turned the public house but in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Keswick Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I ca
n't tell you the year of this because it was a - kind of a legend that was handed down you see. I mean we - we should probably be only one or two years of old - of age when this kind of thing happened. But - he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 tackled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  these men coming out of the boozer an
d - they got him down, on the floor, and they took his whistle. See that was their only means of the police had of calling assistance then, they used to blow their whistles you see. Well they took his whistle, and then - they say that these people said to
 him, now then, Billy, blow it, you see, and that's how he got this nickname. But - he didn't mind. He didn't mind. He was a - actually I - as far as - policemen go I should call him a real good fellow. Oh yes. He - he - he'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 laugh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  sometimes, he - he'd catc
h us you know, and we should see him, and he'd stand and - and look at us and - and smile and say, well I wonder what the little devils are going to do next, before he made any effort to - to stop us. Shall I say he put - we could put it this way, althoug
h he was a good policeman, he was very keen on adult life or anything like that, but for lads you know he - he was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 just one}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 of us. Oh yes, he was a real good sort.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Where you lived obviously once policeman at once was enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Where I lived. In - in - in Narrow Marsh. They - that was a notorious quarter for - roughs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I don't know quite where Narrow Marsh was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - it was - now where - how can I explain it. There was a Roman Catholic church at the corner of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Red Lion Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Now that was
 situated - in Fishergate. Now how I can explain where that was. Well - yes, and Cartergate, now Cartergate now is where the ford - depot is. You know where Cartergate is. Well then Fishergate - you went so far - you went to the bottom of Cartergate, and 
you turned right and that was Fishergate. Right up as far as Hollistown, then {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}London Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 started. Well it was at the corner of London Road and Fishergate, bottom of Hollistown, where this Red Lion Street started and that - went on until it go to Pemberton Street which is not very far, a matter of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 This was a real tough area was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well that wasn't too bad, but it was just when you'd gone by there - in what they reckoned to call the Narrow Marsh, well now this was consisted of - open yards with 
houses in, might be about ten or twelve houses in these yards, six each side kind of, and - that was all down - one side. The other side - there were tall buildings that faced up to the Rock, that Hollistown was built on, the lace market, built on the Roc
k you see. And then it drops suddenly down - to this - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Red Lion Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 and Narrow Marsh. Well then there were tall buildings built up - in front of this Roack, and it was there that the doss houses were - were. They - all these tramps and that used to pay a but fourpence a night, to sleep there, and it was absolutely }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 fifthly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 you know. Nobody bothered about anything, they were really the down and - down and outs. The real tough quarter, well in that quarter, the police used to go in pairs. They never dared go
 in on their own. Because of the slightest pretext - up would go the - the bandwagon and they really got a rough handling down there. But - normally - that I should say was about the worst place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Nottingham
{\*\xmlclose}. It was well known. But normally the - the - the area's would be no worse than - anywhere else. One policeman'd go round on his beat and that's it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you given lessons by anyone before you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, because I went to school that early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How old were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Four. Now the
n this is what I've got here. Now - I started at four years of age, and we went in what they called the infants, but it was the baby class, they called it the babies, in those days. And in that infants there'd be - three classes, and I went - into the bab
i
es, I was there a few weeks, and then went on into the top class as they called it. Jumped the middle one, into the top class. Well that was run by - that was - class was taken by a Miss - Langford, I remember her name. Now the headmistress of the infants
 school was - named Walker, Miss Walker. Now - at - five years of age I went into standard one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 This was all the same school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. Sneinton - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Church{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was it mixed, girls and boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh no. No, the girls were separate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Even from the beginning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh, in the infants, oh yes, it was mixed. Mixed in the infants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What time in the morning did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Nine o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 'Til when?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 And then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Two - 'til four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you go in the afternoon in the infants school as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes, two 'til four.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 And home for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did the hours stay the same in standard one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. Nine 'til twelve. As you - then you went home to dinner, and - two 'til half past four. Half past 
four. That continued right through -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Walked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How long did it take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh - I was fortunate, we wasn't - too far, five or - ten minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Who went with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Usually on your own or if you picked up a pal on the road you'd walk together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 When you were in the baby class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh you'd go on your own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you stay at the same school the whole time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well actually I liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
They were very good. Right throughout the whole - school really, infants, and - shall we say the seniors as they'd call it those days, they were very very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well, not particularly - you - you was given a good training, you was - as being a church of school of course you had a religious - lesson first thing in the morning and - from - onwards from then of course you - normal schooling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about things like manners?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well you got that at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did they do it at school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Not as I know to, unless of course it was a matter of if you saw the teacher - the women teachers - you'd have to - raise your hat, you was taught that kind of thing you see, but otherwise - nothing extraordinary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Tidiness did they emphasise at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well yes, you had to go tidy, they'd look at your hands to make sure you were clean Oh yes, every day. And you were expected to go with clean shoes and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well they were very keen. You either got a red mark which was - on time, or you got a black mark which wasn't. But - they wouldn't - they wouldn't entertain you going - late very often, they'd want to know why.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about ways of speaking? Did they take any notice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well not particularly, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 If you did something the teachers }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 disapproved}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  of, what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well you'd get the strap. That was a - a strap with a - leather strap with a - ha
ndle, and three prongs. Serious - if it was anything serious you'd be sent to the headmaster and he'd use an ordinary cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of things would you get the strap for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh just larking about, talking and so on. Oh yes. Oh yes, if you was lar
king about in the class or - talking - or anything like that, eating sweets if they found it out, you'd get the strap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Where would you get it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 On your hands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 On your hand just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not on your behind?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of things would you get the cane for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - cheeking the teachers or - something like that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 When you were in the baby class what sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 punishments}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 None as I know to. I can't remember anything - any punishment in the infants because as I say I wasn't in it very long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Then when you got to the top class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh the top classes you got this ordinary punishment, I never got it because I was always taught to behave myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Even the little ones would have got it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh at standard one and two, no, I don't think so. No, they - up to I should say about standard three, they'd be more or less - told where they'd gone wrong, and kind of - you know, motherly, they would - women teachers, 
standard one and two. Very good. Very good, I can say that about all the teachers at that school at that period. They were extraordinary good. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork, your real parents and your foster parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, only normal, they'd - if you won a prize, of course they'd be pleased.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you win prizes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I had ones. But - they didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 ake all that - keen interest, you see, for the simple reason that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 as}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 I got along - I usually finished top of the c
lass and things like that, well - that made it that I - if I had have been allowed I'd have been a - had a chance of going to secondary school, or a school of art which I passed for that, but they - they just wouldn't pay the money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What stage did you actually leave school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Leave school? A fortnight before I was thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 But you could have gone on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 They wouldn't pay but you would have been accepted to go on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, I mean - I left - I left school - because I couldn't 
go any higher. I'd been - you see, this - the school went on to standard seven, and then ex-seven. There were about four of us in ex-seven, sat on one - one form together. Well we couldn't go any higher. And I was in ex-seven at eleven years of age.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So you were three years in the top form?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well near enough. From eleven 'til I was a fortnight before thirteen. You couldn't do anything. I used to spend me time helping the headmaster, and - doing checking }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 registers}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 . Running the school library and the
n - very often we should be sent down to these - infants - to - mark their - papers, their sums and things like that you see. You - you wouldn't be doing a lot of school work, unless of course - when - until it came to the - annual - examinations, which w
e had. The school board examinations you know. And then of course we had to sit for them you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So which age was it if you had have been paid for you could have gone to another school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh I should have been - about nine or ten probably, I wouldn't be sure on that age, I couldn't be sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 But when you were about eleven could you have transferred to another school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh no, there's not much transfer in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I thought you felt you should have gone on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes, but I mean - if you - you could - you passed for the secondary school you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 At what age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
It'd be about ten or eleven I should think, I - that I'm not certain of. And - then you'd get - you - if you passed this examination for the secondary school - well the
n you'd - you'd be allowed to go. But - those days you had to pay for all this kind of thing you see, well of course if your parents weren't prepared to pay, then of course you couldn't go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 But you did pass?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Oh yes, I - I could have gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Which school was this you could have gone to?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Mandella. But - as I say, the - the - the - my parents, my own father and - he wouldn't pay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You felt he could didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well I did, yes, because he was getting the money. But you see
 naturally - with not being officially adopted - these foster parents, they - they thought that me own father should pay so much towards me - education, you see. And if he wouldn't pay well they wouldn't. So now - now I've grown older of course I can unde
rstand - more about it, but at that time I felt very frustrated. It was a kind of - you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13508230\charrsid6829132 get}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 that feeling well here I am, I'm doing my best, and - I'm just handicapped. And this happened a time or two during my -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you ever attend any part time education afterwards, evening classes or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No. No, we had to go to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your parents or your foster parents ask what you did at school? Or were they just pleased when you got a prize?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did they ever visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did they meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You mean the children at school? Oh well that was varied, some had a - shall I say - good homes, some had
 bad, according to what part of the district they lived in you see. You see, some parts of Sneinton - were very very poor. And - others down the Dale which was one of the better class districts at the time - they'd - they'd come along perhaps better dress
ed than us and so on you see, but it never made any difference, there was no falling out about where you came from.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I never noticed it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were there any gangs or groups in this school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
It wasn't allowed. If they - they saw - anybody - you know, likely to cause any trouble, well it was nipped in the bud, they were told about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were there any groups in the school as opposed to gangs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 The poor children mixed with the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Oh yes, there was no - what shall I say, class distinction. We were boys and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were there any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not - as I could remember. I've
 never known anyone - left out, except - where - money came in. Well, I mean - such as a - we - we could go to the school - to the baths, Victoria baths, and - by attending the school you could probably go in for a ha'penny, you see, well these poorer chi
l
dren didn't have the ha'penny so - there's there is a possibility that they may have been deprived of it you see. It's the same with the Boys Brigade, I mean, we used to pay - I believe it was - tuppence or threepence - to - a week, you know, to get all t
h
e facilities, but - these poorer children wouldn't have been allowed to go, because they haven't the money. Although they - these Boys Brigades, they did - open their doors to as many as possible. They - you know - brushed things over a little bit for the
m.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You obviously have regrets about your education, do you think you benefitted from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 While you were at school did you have a part time job, can you tell me about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. Oh well now this is where
 we come into the interesting part, not - I've been trying to reckon up - just about - when this would be. See - it'd be - when I was about ten years old. I was - I went part time - that is a way, you know, when you wasn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 at}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  school, to a - a stationer's s
hop in Goosegate. Now - the hour - the hours - were - at - the dinnertime, I used to go from school, before I went home, was on me way, and tell mother I was going you see. And - I should get there about ten minutes past twelve. And from then}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 'til - one o'
clock - you run errands, and things like that. Tidy up the shop, things like that. Of an evening - you'd leave school at four thirty - you'd go home and have your tea. And you'd get to work - as soon as you could after five. See, probably be - five minute
s
 past five or something like that, round about five. And then of course - you'd have errands again. And - this fellow used to do - take on orders for printing, and that all - he used to deal with a - little printing firm on Hollowstone which meant walking
 
all through the - the graveyards of Barkergate and so on, that was the nearest cut, through back alleys and so on, onto to Hollowstone where this printers works was, bring the printing back if it was done. Then there'd be - taking out books and so on, goi
ng to Sisson and Parkers ordering these books for him and so on. And then - you spent your time like that, and I should be there 't perhaps - nine, half past, ten o'clock.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you a big boy at ten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well I was tall. But - usually between nine an
d ten, except - for Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays, and I was allowed to go at seven, so that I could go to choir practice. But - Tuesdays, Thursdays and Saturdays you'd be expected to - stay late, in fact I've been there almost as late as twelve o'clock
 on a Saturday evening. Walking as far as - Sherwood - to take exercise books to a private school in - Devon Drive. Almost up 'til twelve o'clock at night. Then for this princely - you got the princely sum of half a crown a week. A week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How did you get the job? Was it through your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
No. The - the - this stationers shop were run by two brothers. One kept the shop and the other worked in the chemists shop which I - eventually - went to work at. You see. And - the young chap across the yard -
 worked for the chemist at the time and he knew this job was going you see so I - I went and got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you feel that half a crown a week was a fair wage or not at that stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - it was a matter of just thinking you was earning something. V
alues didn't come into it at those days, I mean you were - you were just earning something, you was doing something to help. And that was it. Now this is the time - when I say - I'm - not we'll give you the Saturday morning. This was the first - first thi
n
g. You get there at nine. First job was clear out his fire, in the back place, make him a fire. Then you'd have to sweep up his back place, sweep out the shop. After you'd swept the shop out - you'd have - his - windows to clean on the bottom floor at the
 back. There was a place where you used to sit you know when he wasn't in the shop. And - then the shop windows. Because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What time had you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Nine o'clock. And - you'd clean his windows, shop windows, you see, and - then about - ten o'clo
ck, or eleven, anywhere - no fixed time particular, he used to take a walk down Sneinton market. And he'd leave me at that age - in charge of the shop well if we had any customers - I had to - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 sell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 . You see, and put the money in the till. Well then - that 
was all right, he'd come back again about an hour later, and check up. And after dinner - was a very slack period. So I was lent out - to the fellow opposite, who kept - home made sweet shop. Now - whether he paid - this fellow in the sweet shop paid this
 
- anything for my assistance I don't know, but I used to go over there and - turn his freezer, make his ice cream for him, and then - turn the handle on his - sweet machine, the mould you know, making his sweets, and so on, that spent most of the afternoo
n. Oh I'm missing something. Saturday dinner, at twelve o'clock - I had to go and fetch this fellow's - dinner. He lived at - Ladybay at Bridgford. Now I had to walk - yes, from - this shop, to these - graveyards, down Hollowstone, along 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}London Road, West{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} B
ridgford to Ladybay to - his home, and there his mother'd - pack up a dinner, and although she'd be cooking - she'd never offer you a cake or a tart or anything. Nothing and then you'd walk back with this dinner. Of course consequently when you got back i
t was cold you see. Well then -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you have any dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
No, not with him. Not with him. Yes, I went home for dinner. Then - while he had his dinner I'd go home for mine. Well when you came back again, you'd be expected to wash all his dinner po
ts up, he'd warm it up on his bit of a stove. But he wouldn't allow you to put a kettle on to get warm water, you had to wash his greasy pots in cold water. A right messy job. Well then of course I come on to this afternoon, I was lent to this sweet - fel
l
ow. And - that spent most of the Saturday afternoon. I should go home for my tea. And then come back - and - what happened there after tea, oh I used to be messing about in the shop or running these errands where - you know, to take these books out to the
s
e various private schools or anything like that.. He kept me fully occupied I'll tell you that. And - and then you'd carry on 'til - late in the evening. 'Til such time as he said you could go home, and then he'd give you your half a crown, and this fello
w across the road, I used to go across there and he'd give me a - a bag of sweets, for - my help in the afternoon and that's as far as I know about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 In the school holidays did-you work longer hours for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No, everything was kept normal. Kept normal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How did he actually treat you as a person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well I think he more or less - looked down on you, this fellow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How did you feel about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, not much. I didn't care much for him, but - as I say, it was a matter of just - getting some - some money and that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What happened to the money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well I used to give the half crown to me foster mother and she used to give me sixpence back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did having a job alter your attitude to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No, I enjoyed school right through to the finish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How did you feel about the work itself? Did you like it or dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well, when I worked at the stationers shop - I didn't care for it a great deal, because - I don't know, I may - well I don't know exactly h
ow to put it. There was no prospects, you was going to be there - all your time, you know, there was nothing extraordinary, nothing to interest you much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How long did you stay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh I think probably twelve months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 And then what happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well then - this - lad across the yard left the chemist shop - and I went to work for the chemist, half time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Can you tell me about hours and everything there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh this was a lot better. In the first place, the chemist's name was Smith, Mr Smit
h. And - he'd got two shops. The top shop was at the top of Sneinton Road agen the church. The bottom shop was on Lambeth Street, and - old Mr Smith kept the - bottom shop, and the son, he was a - chemist, he - kept the shop where the house was where they
 
lived you see. And - they were both very nice, very nice people. And it - I used to go to work there about half past eight in the morning, on a - oh now wait a minute, now this is school time. The school time you'd go - in the dinner hour as usual. From a
bout - just after twelve 'til one. And - and then you'd - during that time you'd take out - medicines, you see, people had a lot - he had a lot of private people then you see. Until this - National Health came out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were they all done up with white paper and sealing wax?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
That's right, yes, and you had a little tin box like a kidney shaped box hung over your shoulder, you know, and these medicines were put in, and you'd take them out to these different - different people, that was - mostly - dinner 
time, see. Because he wasn't a - a bad fellow, he wouldn't - give you a job to do that he knew you couldn't do in that time without rushing about. He was a very good fellow. And then - after tea you'd start about half past five. And - you'd go down to the
 
bottom shop and - see if he wanted anything. If not oh well it'd be a question of perhaps well go up and see if - Mr Willie as he called him, wanted - anything at the top shop. And then if he did - I should have to come down to the bottom shop and carry t
his stuff up to the top shop. And - because the bottom shop was used more or less as a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 store place}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 as well you see. And between the two shops you'd go like that you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of stores did chemists carry, did they sell other things or was it all drugs then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well - well, no, they - they - they sold a lot of vinegar, that was in the vinegar barrels. They do - there's a lot of distilled water which they used - for various medicines, although a lot of the medicines were tap water of course, out 
of the ordinary tap. And - then there'd be such stocks as - pills or - baby foods and so on, they'd be kept in stock you see. And - well, anything that they sold in the shop. You see, I mean if a traveler was to come in he'd go to the bottom shop, to see 
t
he - old Mr Smith. Not - he wouldn't - go up to the top shop. And the top shop'd order his stuff from the bottom shop and I used to have to carry it about and so on. But - it was not such hard work, as the - the stationer's shop, because he really was a -
 
an understanding man this, he was - he was really like another father to me this Mr Smith, and Mrs Smith was very good. Sat - sat - on Saturdays you'd - you'd sweep the shops out of course, there's a lot of sawdust used those days for floors, we should sw
e
ep the shop out and - and just keep things tidy. The things that were - down below, you know, without getting on the ladders you'd have to dust and so on, keep the shop generally clean. And Saturday afternoon - after - if there was no - orders or anything
 
to take out, no medicines or anything to take out I should - he'd say, well go and help the servant in the kitchen at the top shop and - between us we should get the tea ready. Well I used to like that because - Mary, the servant, she was a nice girl, and
 - she'd say, well - ask Mrs - Mrs Smith if you can have a cake. Or - they used to eat a lot of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 pickles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 those days, I should toast them at the fire you know, see and - as Mrs Smith'd come through she'd say to Mrs Smith well - what about letting him have a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 pickles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 or something like that you see. And Mrs Smith, being a - she was a really - a motherly woman, she would do, were very good, a lot different to this stationer fellow altogether, and - that's mostly how I spent - Saturday afternoon, getting on towards
 teatime, then of course Saturday evening it'd be a question of - doing what other jobs I'd got to do such as - cleaning the - mortar and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 pestle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  if they'd been mixing powders and that up or - keeping the ointment nice, clean, and the slab that they mixed the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 ointment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 on, generally keeping things clean and so on you see. And - about - eight o'clock or half past eight - Mrs Smith used to get old Mr Smith's supper ready, he'd have cocoa and - a few sandwiches. And then for a time the servant used to take i
t down to him. Then eventually - I'd be going home about that time, half past eight, to nine o'clock.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So we're about 1925?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Roughly I should say, I mean, these dates - they're not - they're - they've got to be near enough. But this is the patter
n of the - the life as you're asking it you see. Well then - they offered me another job - which I took, but it - it wasn't a very satisfactory job you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 In the half hose department you see, they changed the department.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Still as a knitter was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh as a knitter, been a knitter all my life. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 
then - I - came out of work abai\{missing\}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  because this was - well the whole of the trade was seasonal, you know, you'd - you'd perhaps be off - a mon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6374543\charrsid6829132 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  - a month, or two months
, perhaps about March while they're changing the orders over to - the summer - type of - work you see and then later on in the year about October you'd be out of work again, while they - were getting the winter orders away you see, it was a seasonal trade
 
at that time. It's not like it is now. Now is one continuous work right the way through but those days was - you're in, you was out and so on you see. But I got fed up with that place like that because as I say I started to get - resentful of these variou
s
 ways and methods of going on. I remember once going into the factory - and - there was a long counter, about four foot from the wall. And - we were supposed to stand against this wall, it was a crime to - stand up to the counter. And - I remember going i
n one day and this - the - manager - director, Grundy was his name one of these straight up men with his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 pince-nez}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 in his hand you know, thought he was something you know, and - with being in the Army of course it - it had made us a little bit tough and rou
gh you see. And - I went in one day and I happened to stand against the counter. And I can re - see him now, picking up one of these ebony rules, you know, these round }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 ebony}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  rules and rapping my knuckles with it. He said, your place is against the wall. An
d then of course I did really lose my temper. I said, look - I said, don't you think I've held this wall up long enough Working for this firm. I said, if you touch me again with that thing, I says, I shall fetch your head clean from your shoulders, and th
a
t - of course that did it. I never did very well after that, I didn't - he didn't sack me, but I - I didn't do very well, I was a marked man after that. There were two of us actually - a fellow named Wilson, they used to call him Tug Wilson, he was a litt
l
e bit tough as well you see and we'd - been going to these union meetings and we were beginning to realize - how - we were being cheated, we were not being treated fairly you see. And I remember this boss - this Grundy saying to us - I'd sooner anybody ha
ve come back from the services than your two. That was the way he - he - he looked at matters then you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So what did you do next?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - well then eventually - I got in touch with a fellow and he got me a job. He - he knew where there was a j
ob going, Frettingham's it was, on the - top of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Thoroughton Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, in Radford. And they told me that if I could get a runner on, that's a girl, that run the tops on - I could start there the following week. So I went - and - saw a girl that was running on
 ribs for me at that time - and I said well now look, would you like to go and - have another job, because she was really working under slave conditions. She was working - for about four men running ribs on, and put bottoms as we called it in between, and
 
the whole of the money she could earn was twenty seven shillings a week, that was as much as she could earn. And - she said, how much would they pay me and - I said, well you'd better go and see them, so I told her where to go and she went and - she came 
b
ack the following morning and said that - that she'd accepted the job, so then of course I went up to this firm, I said, well now, this runner on will come with me and we'll start - on Monday. When I - went back to see Morleys about it they said, ah well,
 
you can't go, we'll give you - you've got to give a week's notice. I said, oh no. Not after the way you've treated me, I said, oh no. I said, I'm going on Monday, I said, I know one of these lads in this factory here that can take my place, I says, so the
r
e'll be no loss of production for you people, I said, but take it as you like. I am not coming here next Monday. Oh we shan't give you your insurance cards and we shan't do this, we shan't do the other. I said, all right, you keep 'em I said, but I shall 
g
o down to Labour Exchange and get a set of me own. I was turning - a rebel. You see. The - the attitude of these people, they - they treated you like so much dirt, if you'd let 'em. And - you were gradually, we was - I was turning - into a real rebel. And
 - we started at this other firm, and I - the first - week - that we worked there - my wages - jumped up about another - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 pound}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 odd or more a week. And the girl, they paid her fifty shillings as a set wage. Now that was a big - nearly double you see. And - w
e worked together, this - girl and myself on this - for this one machine you see. She was only doing the work for me you see, and she's getting nearly double the money. And - we went on there for oh - quite - some years. And - well she was working for me 
-
 when I got married. That was in 1923. So - you can judge how many - how long we worked - together on this - for this one firm. And I might say on the record, that this firm of Frettingham's - the - father - and the mother, Mrs Frettingham, were really - 
very nice people to work for. Very nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So how long did you stay there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
I stayed there - now what happened then? Frettingham's. Oh, now wait a minute. Now - now - what happened then - was that - this - Mr Frettingham, the father of the - the fat
her, he told me that his one ambition in life was to have a factory of his own, with his own name over the door. Because they were a - actually in rooms in a factory let off in rooms you see at that time, they had so many rooms. And he wanted a factory of
 his own. Well now he was having one built, on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hucknall Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Now - this thing leaked out, in the press, of course everybody got to know about it you see, we read about it and - the old man - old man Frettingham he was - really - annoyed about it. We were g
oing to have a party and - you know, open this factory in fine style, but - anyway in the meantime - he decided to go to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Just on a visit, and it - he was - advised by his doctors not to go. But he would go. And - what happened then was he had a -
 coming back on the boat he had a stroke. And - instead of - getting his wish that he wanted to - walk into the factory, he was - had to be pushed about in a wheelchair. And he never went into that factory. He wouldn't go in, because - just because he cou
ldn't walk in, and it was left then to the sons - to run that. Oh and I think I worked for them - eighteen, nineteen years. And then - after that, now of course you're getting on into - well in - above what you want. You see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you ever anything other than a knitter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So you were a knitter till retirement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You retired seven years ago did you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. 1964.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Would you have preferred another type of occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well apart from - being the - chemist - I'd 
have loved to have been that of course but - that of course as I say, that's one of the frustrations and it didn't - didn't happen, you see, but I got interested enough into the hosiery trade that - and - when I was at work, the money wasn't too bad, you 
s
ee, as - as the years went on, the - and the machines got better you - you was able to earn more money, and then gradually this statement was discontinued and different arrangements were made - by the unions, so that - that the money did go up. When you w
ere at work, you did get the decent money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 To go back before 1918 now, did you belong to any trade union then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. You had to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 From what age did you join?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 It was a closed shop was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 More or less. There were 
some first working without the union. Butmost of the well known fires, you had to join the union, even as a boy. When you started from school as a lad, under the man, you still - you had to join a union, oh yes. Oh yes, the boys had to join.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Before 1918 did you take part in any of its activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, I was a - a shop steward in the - the Frettingham's factory for quite a while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 This is post-war isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 At the very beginning did you take part in activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No, because I mean we were on - we were too young you see before we joined up
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Before 1918 did you then feel that employers and workers had the same interests or different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What do you mean by interests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were they out for the same things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 Well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
, if - if you mean that the employers were out to get as - what they could for a little money as possible, I should say yes. You see. But we were fairly well protected by this hosiery trade union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You feel it was a good union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. It was
 a union where things were properly thrashed out, for quite a while. In fact it - it's a union I think up 'til today - you could number the disputes on one hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Is it a very old union, was it one of the earlier ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, it was - it - it mu
st have been going some years before I - I joined it, I really don't know when it was - inaugurated at all, I can't tell you that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you feel that in those days there were great divisions of interest among the workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Interests, well now I ca
n't quite - grasp what you mean by interests. Do you mean, one man trying to get a better job than another? Well, there was always that kind of thing, I mean - where - wherever you go it was only human nature to have little bits of jealousies wasn't it, I
 mean that's human nature. And - if one man could got a better job than another there might have been a little bit of dissension but not - to cause - any uproar shall we say.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Some people say that in those days there was a great division between trained craftsmen and other workers, did you feel that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Aye. I mean - in this public house where these - men used to go - worked for Morleys, you know - they had a room of their own. A knitter's room. Oh yes. Well it - it's only just a matt
er of - of this public house was at the bottom of Newark Street, and - there was room set aside and - these men, these knitters - they could go in any room of the pub - as they liked you see. But - there was one room set aside for them and they'd usually 
c
ongregate in there. Now, in a morning before six o'clock - the - the most of 'em'd go and have a - a run and coffee before they started. Before starting you see. Well they'd all congregate in this room, you see. Well then of course if there was any - disc
ussions going on about the firm or - the work or anything like that, it was - discussed over this coffee and stuff you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What did you do about your breakfast break?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well I - I did - well most of them did, but I was lucky, I only lived a few minutes away, and I used to nip off home and get it you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Would you say that full time work changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Full time work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You'd been working so much part time before you started full time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, well - I mean, no, it - it didn't make any difference, it - it became part of your life and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you treated differently once you became a full time worker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh no. Oh no, no, no, No, no, the family was - was a - a - shall we say - a
 good family, it was a - it was - to put the word what it means, it was a real family life, it made no difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I wondered if you were treated as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 suddenly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  growing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well you - probably you - the foster mother and the other - me own parents 
would regard you as a growing lad and that was all. You become - you'd go - shall we put it like this, you'd go from a youth, a boy - to - a young man, you can put it like that, you see. And - you'd probably regarded as being able to form your own decisio
ns better and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Many people divide society into different social classes or groups. In that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another? You've told me about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West Bridgford{\*\xmlclose}
, can you enlarge on this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh
 - well - no, you - you'd find it everywhere, I mean, there was - always that - shall we say underneath the surface - the - if you lived in the poorer - parts of the town, you see - you'd be looked upon as scruffs shall I say you see. While those people -
 
say living in various - other - district - parts of the town you see, I mean that Sneinton Dale was really - a good - a - shall we say - a step above Sneinton, they were more - oh I can - what word can I use for it - they're they're a little bit above, bu
t
 - they weren't snobbish, like the West Bridgford people, the West Bridgford people had got an idea that they was the Lord Almighty. They were something right above you. You see. But no, the Dale was a better - better - quality district - than the - this 
- pay - place where we lived in Sneinton, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Below Sneinton I suppose you'd get Narrow Marsh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
You'd come down to the Narrow Marsh. Sneinton was more shall we say - if you could like to put the classes - Narrow Marsh were the tramps, the vag
rants, and so on. Very low, you see, couldn't care less type of people. And - then you come to the Sneinton which would - you'd - could call middle class. And then you'd go to - round the Dale quarter and that where they were a little bit better off and t
he - the - the streets were - kept better and so on, the houses were better built, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 we\rquote ll}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 put it that way, which gave the environment a better environment. You - you'd ca that - upper middle class, and then of course you got these - snooty lot in Bridgford w
hich they - you could call good class because they'd got houses with baths in. Where - water closets and so on, where at down Sneinton they were all these - tubs, you see, there was no water closets, no taps in a good lot of the houses. There were in some
 
of course, I'm speaking generally now. You'd find that - a tap in the yard, and you had to go - to that tap and take water in a bucket into the house, and so on you see. There's no facilities for - hot water. What hot water you - you - you wanted you had 
to either boil it on a stove, a gas stove, or - on your fire. Well - now - where me own mother lived - they had - when they washed, they had to have a bucket on top of the ordinary fire, see, to boil the water, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 boil}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  the clothes in you see. And the conditions were very - very bad, very bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So do you feel it depended where you lived very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 It helped a lot. It helped a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What class would you say you belonged to yourself then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well it'd be the middle class. The middle.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of people belonged to the same class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well most of the people round that district.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of jobs would they have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh the jobs were varied, I mean, there was a - there were quite a lot of jobs those days - street - sweepi
ng - there were a lot of people in the lace trade and - various - various trades, you couldn't - they worked at almost anything you see, because - most of them those days were - be either labourers or craftsmen, I mean, just according to what - how they t
ook life you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of people belonged to the other classes you've mentioned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well - in the - first place, the Narrow Marsh people, they'd be tramps. Vagrants. You see. A scruffy lot that - who - never thought about washing or shaving or 
anything like that, they'd be real dirty. And they used to go - out on the roads and then go into - Narrow Marsh - doss houses as we called 'em, to - to sleep at night, you see. Actually - they were a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 vicious}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  lot, if you upset them - they'd - they coul
d cause trouble. But - then there was - our lot, the - the working - working class people, you could call them that. Lived round Sneinton or the Dale district or anywhere like that, they were all working class people. And then of course you got these in -
 Bridgford which were mostly the clerks and so on. So on like that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No, we were taught that we were all human beings. And - we were taug
ht to - to treat life - as a human being, if you could help - anyone - you helped them, and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you ever told to touch your cap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, as a - as a schoolboy. As a schoolboy, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Show respect in some way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes, as a schoolboy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 After that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well after you went to work of course you gradually began to - shell we say grow up, I'll put it like that, and there was not - there were quite a lot of people that - that would do that kind of thing because - in some cases it did help them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
You see, I mean with their jobs, I mean if they went to the job - to say the boss, and give him a bit of soft soap as we used to call it you see well naturally - some of the bosses would - advance that man at the first opportunity.
 But - for myself and this is a survey on me own life, I should say - no, I never kowtowed or - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 bowed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  down to anyone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was there anyone you had to call sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, there were plenty as we were supposed to call sir in the factories, but I 
was one of those people, I never cared for man nor beast. And I would never say sir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents or foster parents in these ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did I have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember anyone else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh no. No. I d
on't - I can't say for me own father because I mean - he worked for the Corporation but - this man that worked for me foster father - he was treated as one of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 In the district you lived in who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh now you're asking. The - well, I - I just - well - the publicans were - were - were people that - they - they stood out a mile for the simple reason there were so many public house in the district - that you - that you couldn't miss them. I mean now, 
I'll give you an instance now we'll take Sneinton Road for itself, for - this is one road, the road that we lived on. Now you start up against the church, there was the Fox Inn. Then come a little bit further down - on the right hand side, this is going d
o
wn the road, the right hand side you've got the Bull Fry. A little bit lower down on the left hand side was the Queen's Arms. Opposite that was a - off licence. Now a little bit lower down on the right hand side there was the New Inn, that was straight op
posite where I lived. A little bit further down on the left hand side - was - another - off licence. Straight opposite that was the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Windsor{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Castle{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} public house. A little bit lower down than that was the Smiths Arms. On the left hand side. And on the right hand side right at the bottom was the Wheatsheaf.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 How many yards is this? A quarter of a mile?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh no, no, no, no, no, between the - the Fox - that is the first one, to the Bull Prior, you might get about - two hundred yards and that was at - that was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13508230\charrsid6829132 furthest}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 . From the Bull Prior down to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Queens{\*\xmlclose}
 Arms it - it'd only - matter be about - thirty yards. You see. Then down to the New Inn you might get about fifty yards, and down to the - the other one, that - that - Windsor Castle - that' be - pe
rhaps about - a hundred yards or more. Then the Smiths Arms'd only be about a hundred yards and - the Wheatsheaf'd only be about a hundred yards, and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were the publicans actually thought of as important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - that's where most of
 the people spent their leisure time. The grown ups. You see, those times - those time of days - you could - you could take children into the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 boozers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  you see, and so - there was none of that where - restraint on them at all, they'd go and they'd take the
 children and - for the life of me I don see why they can't have children in now, but I mean that's - how it was then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You've mentioned all these pubs, was there a lot of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 drunkenness}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  round there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh - oh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Or were they well behaved ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh no. Oh no, there were brawls - odd nights, but - Saturday night was a regular - prize fighting night, when they all turned out you see, I mean - the - they - they kept on - open very late at night, you see. And - when they came out the men - were rea
lly well - primed for fighting you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of things did they fight about, anything special?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh I can't - I can't tell you, anything that cropped up, I think it was a - part of the life, I mean if they hadn't had a damned good fight well when they - they hadn't seen life, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you say your grandfather was a fighter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 He was a prize fighter, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 A real prize fighter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. But not - he wasn't a noted man. You see, he used to - he used to fight with 'em perhaps 
as regards training or things like that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you say he once gave you a hiding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh he saw me in the street and I got a hiding from a lad and - he took me in and - he said, well what's the good of me trying to teac
h you - and - I got a hiding and - good clout and so on and sent out to - have another go at this youth, you see, he was a - you was taught right from the start, you stand on your own - two feet. There was none of this moly-coddling lark as there is today
. Not in - in my life. I'm not saying about everyone else, I mean I've known friends of mine, schoolfriends - where they've had a different type of life altogether to what I had.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about the shopkeepers in your area, who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well most of themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about the clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh the clergy, now we're talking about the Sneinton church clergy I presume. Well in the first place the vicar was - be Reverend - Honourable Dalrymple. He was the - now I believe he was the so
n - of the Earl of Dalkeith. Now he was a real good fellow. And - now - I told you before that he paid - when Sneinton church - was restored a bit - now what date was that, about 19 - 1912 I think, the chancel was all restored. And - this - shall I put it
 was hearsay. But - I was told - that he paid for the marble on the floor of the chancel, out of his own pockets. But he was a real good - clergyman. Real good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you come into contact with him much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, as a - as a choirboy, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about the teachers is your area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 The teachers at Sneinton school I can class them as all first class people. They were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well that - that I - I don't know. The teacher in the - that taught - the fifth standard, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hamilton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 his name - he was the choirmaster. And - the one that taught standard six, seven and ex-seven - there were three classes in one room at that separated you see, and - he - he was a choirman, he - he was in the choir as well so - I should imagine 
that their - they associated a lot together, but we didn't know - much of their private lives at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You wouldn't know about farmers in that area would you, who they associated with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well that we can
't say you see because I mean - at those - kind of days you - you was satisfied to be a working man and you didn't bother what anybody else did. You see, it was a community that - although you were willing to help anyone that were in trouble, anyone that 
you knew that was of course, you - you left it at that. You didn't inquire into what they did, why they didn't have - how they spent their life, everybody else - lived their lives of their own. There was no praying into other people's lives.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You said what a helpful person your foster mother was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh yes, she was. I mean she'd - anyone round about there, they'd got anyone ill - yes, well she - if anyone was sick, or anything like that, in the - in the near neighbourhood - she'd go and sit with them
, and - spend - the night, giving relief to those people that were looking after them during the day you see. And then of course - if they recovered OK. If they didn't, and they died, well - she'd say, well - leave it to me, I'll - get you an undertaker. 
And that, well of course - she was - well known to - a fellow named Botham, or - Thomas Botham or he was in - he'd got a place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Sneinton Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 you see. Well she used to lay this dead person out, you see, and - then - we'd send for - Bottom more and he'd 
come up and - measure them you know and - get the coffin made and - carry the funeral through. And of course she used to have a little bit of a rake-off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Right, well now we'll get to where she - she used to get a bit of a rake-off off of this Thomas 
Bottomoere for - for the order you see, and - she'd do this as often as she was required, you see, to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you sent out in the night sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, sometimes you'd be - you'd be called up in the night and she'd say, well just run down to T
ommy Bottomore's - and tell him to come up to this - house where she was you know. Well that used to scare me stiff because - he'd let me in the front door and - all this - funeral trappings were lying about you know, the shrouds and things like that were
 hanging around in his shop, and - with being a youngster of course it did really scare me a bit, but - you had to take it all in good part, that was a - it was a job - she expected you to do it and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of people would you say went to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well now you're asking a man that's - that's views on church have - altered vastly since the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 This is pre-1918 don't forget.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well I should say that almost the same as they are today, they - some believed in it and some didn't
, some went because they - it benefited their businesses and so on, you see. It was a kind of a mixed bag shall we say, so me went because they believed and some because it was a - a - they could gain by it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of people went to the chapels?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well I never had much dealing with chapel people but I should imagine they were - a little bit more religious, than what the church people were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was there any sort of feeling between the two where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not as I know to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living, or would you say there were different groups?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well more or less the - the standard of living was the same, the wages were the same, I mean - whatever trade you was in th
ere was not a great difference as regards the wage standard. But - some - some trades of course they - they were fully occupied and like out trade, ours was seasonal. I mean it just made that slight bit of difference, but - as regards their standard of li
ving I don't think there was anything different. I mean food was cheap - your wages was down, and so on you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you think that one group felt itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, I don't think I should say that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You've already said that some families were thought of as rough and others as respectable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well - in - in the district where I lived - they were all more or less alike, until you got of course down to this - upper middle class, they might think they're a - little bit different, but you find the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 highest}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  difference came between - the - the people in Nottingham and the people over the Trent in Bridgford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 A distinction? I shouldn't call it a lot of distinction. No, they were more or less alike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 patch}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  other to people in different social classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about your foster parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 They were the same, everyone was - friendly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about your foster mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 They were all the same, they were all working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 There was no need because it was all one class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well if you mean in my younger days - when you say described as a - as a gentleman, in the first place, if they - if you're 
talking about what I should describe as a gentleman, I should say in the first place - I should say the vicar. He was a real gentleman. And - then of course this - fellow that I worked for in the chemist shop. They were real - real gentlemanly people, and
 
his wife was - what shall we class - say a gentlewoman, they were really good people. They went to church, they went to St Mary's church, except the times - in the evening when I was singing the solo at Sneinton church. Then they'd attend there. You see. 
But they - did really - live - a churchman's life, we'll put it that way. They really - were - believed in it, and their - and their actions - were churchgoing actions shall we say. They were real good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember anyone being described as a real lady apart from this one you've just mentioned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well I - they didn't describe people those days, they were - you - you were either good, you're - or - or bad or indifferent. Nobody bothered so much about - who you were, what you were. If - the - the 
- the thing of life in those days, as I knew it, mind you as I've said before, this is - life as I knew it, you might get another person - that'd give a different description of life - at the same - year as this is. You see? But no - we were - were all tr
eated alike. There was nothing extra special. The - you might say - Mrs so and so, well she'd be the same as the next Mrs so and son, and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did anyone outside the home help your own mother look after her house or family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not as I know to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No relatives or friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Not as I know to, no, you see me mother's people were in Ruddington. And - the - me father, well - he didn't want any help. You see, I mean - family life in the days all - mostly hung round the mother. 
Father's I mean they went to work, they went and had a drink and that was it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about your foster mother, did she ever get any help, well she helped other people didn't she, did anyone ever help her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes. Well - wash days, my own mother - wo
uld go down and give her a lift with the washing or go down and do a little bit of cleaning for her you see. To - for a few shillings a week probably you see, but - it wouldn't be - a continuous employment. She'd go down Monday morning and help with the w
ash, you see, perhaps about an hour or an hour and a half. And - then perhaps during the week, one day during the week she may go down and - perhaps do her a bit of dusting for one morning. Nothing fixed shall we say apart from the washing on Monday.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Which your own mother regularly helped her with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 She usually went down to do this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 If your mother or your foster mother were ill or confined to bed how did they manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Best they could, that's the only way I can explain it. You see usually 
the neighbours would come in. You see. I mean, those days - whatever - any adversity happened - to a family - they always used to find that - that - the neighbours - all came in to give them a lift. It was part of life. There was nothing isolated all, the
y
 - they'd come and they'd say, well - right, Mrs Flower's ill today, well now then - I'm going down to the shops, I'll bring her a bit of stuff up, she'd come in and say, is there anything you want, and - and then another neighbour'd come in and look afte
r
 the - me sisters and so on, and - one'd come in and say, well right, I'll scrub out for you, because those days - there - there wasn't carpet sweepers, it was all scrubbing you see, I'll come and scrub your kitchen out for you, now don't you worry, you s
top in bed 'til the - you get right. And that's how life was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your parents have any friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - me foster parents did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What friends did they have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - well they were usually people in the public house business because as I'v
e said before - he - his trade - came through there you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your foster mother have friends of her own?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well only neighbours, round about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were friends ever invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Odd time - odd times, not - this was not
 a regular occurrence. But if they wanted to call they called you see. But - now we're coming to another anecdote. Now - at New Year - New Year's Eve - now - me foster father - foster mother, and a few of their friends and the publicans round about you kn
o
w, they'd all congregate about five minutes to twelve - at the Bath - clock, the clock at the Baths. It's still there, yes. Well they'd congregate there, and then as the clock struck twelve, it was - you know, join hands, Auld Lang Syne, singing - in the 
s
treet you see. Then they'd - mostly - they'd go to one of the houses, you see, if it was a - say a publican, you wouldn't go into the - public bar, you'd go into his - living quarters, and sometimes they'd come to ours and they'd have a drink and - a few 
mince pies or - you know, bit of seasonable food and - that was it. But that - that was one of the things that was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 regular}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 occurrence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Anything else special like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Not as I know to particular, except of course these races, when it was the races this - yes, I told you about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements, what do you feel your parents or foster parents did when they got together with their friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well all that they'd do 
is to - sit and have a - a drink. And a - a meal, we'll put it like that you see. Because I mean there was nothing else really as - as they could do, I mean - there was only a matter of - sport - you see, which wasn't as flourishing those days as it is no
w, you see, people didn't take that keen interest in it like they do now, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about music or singing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, all that - all - all that happened, some of 'em had an old gramaphone, you know with a horn attached and so on, but - me own father
 had one but I - I think it was only for the use of the family. It - at that time you see the gramaphone was just being discovered. Just being brought out, well - for a time it was a novelty. And then - it's like everything else that was a novelty, it's d
ied it's death for a time you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was your own home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I wanted to ask whether you saw anything of the landlord in either house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. It was rented. But - I think me own mother's house - I think I saw the landlady about tw
ice in a lifetime. Mind you she used to call weekly for the re but I wouldn't be there. Probably while I was at school or something like that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you know what you felt about her as a landlady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I had no interest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about your other foster home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Had no interest either. It didn't matter to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Do you remember feeling that your real parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well now this is a difficult question, because as I've said before me father earned very very 
good money. But he spent it on - booze, and - betting and thing like that. And me mother had - really did have a - rough time. It was a rough time she had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So she had a struggle but he didn't?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 But he didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was he ever ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you ever know anyone get any help from the Guardians or the Parish or any charity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 So you can't tell us how they were treated?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, they were too proud. Mind you, I do know - an occasion - where this - foster mother -
 had a nephew living with them, and they went on a holiday - which they did annually, a fortnight's holiday, and - this nephew - stole a shilling. Now - for that shilling - she - totally disowned him. And he had to go into - what was then Bagthrope.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Which was what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
The workhouse. And I remember going up there - odd times to take him a little bit of tobacco and a few sweets, sent by this foster mother. And I - I knew what the - the - the world was like, - it had just got the iron bedstead and each
 - occupant had a - an armchair at the side of the bed, it was an armchair, a wooden armchair, and a locker. Bare floors and - things were - you know, really poor. But - mentioning that where she turned him out the house for the sake of a shilling gives s
ome idea of how strictly they regarded life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 It wasn't even a borrow, it was a real steal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 He - he stole it. You see, and someone came to pay a shilling off of a - the money as they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 owed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  you see, because he used to make a suit for someone and - 
and then - they'd pay so much a week you see. And - someone had brought this shilling in during the time they were on their holidays, and - this fellow - had spent it sooner than - put it down on the paper you see. And - they regarded it as a big crime, a
 shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 It got someone else into trouble as well probably for not paying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well no, it - no, they just - said all right, well all right, if you'll steal a shilling you'll steal anything else and that was it, that's the way they regarded things, that was the way I was brought up, so strict you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 I'd like to ask you about your life at home after you left school. You stayed with your foster mother then didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you spend Sunday any differently now you'd left school? Were you still going to church so often or did you stay in the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
No, I was in the choir 'til the - me voice broke. Now I can't tell you what age that was. But - when you - left school, and you got - and I left the choir - they; I - I didn't atten
d the church - quite so much. But - I'd always got a keen regard for it, we'll put it that way, because - I'd been baptized at Sneinton church And I - insisted on getting married - at Sneinton church. And then - when my son was born - although he was born
 
in Radford, I had him christened in Sneinton church you see, because that church life in my younger days, it become - part of my life. You see, whatever - sport we - we went in for or anything like that was more or less concerned with the church, either t
h
e church or the church school, the normal school, see. But - I - apart from that I don't think things altered a great deal, I didn't go to church quite so often you see and then the - of course - going to work, you - you're - you mixed with a - other boys
 
as well you see what used to work with and so on and you had various - occupations, I mean at that time of day, the - the princess - roller skating rink opened on - Castle Boulevard. That about - that was about that time, well - one of the boys that I kne
w - his - one of his relatives - was a - a skating instructor there, and we'd go down - when the - the place was closed to the public, and he'd - give us lessons in roller skating and so on you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What other sort of things did you do in your spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well after we left school I'm blowed if I know. This is one of the things that - because there - there was no organised - entertainment you know, there was nothing organised, you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you give up hopscotch and cricket and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh yes, you had to do that when - when I first went to work at half time, part time you - you had no time, because you was working 'til eleven o'clock at night you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Were you walking and cycling still?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Oh yes, we kept on walkin
g, doing walks and cycling, in fact we've walked miles - I mean the time we were courting, we used to go - to - Beeston - by - train walk down to the side of the Trent, walk along the side of the Trent - to - Barton, or opposite Barton - village, we'd go 
across the Trent in the ferryman's boat, into Barton - village, we'd go across the Trent in the ferryman's boat, into Barton, and there we should have a - a tea. Well now, the tea in those days for - we used to pay a shilling each.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What year are we in now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
In Barton. Oh this would be when I was courting so - you'd be coming up to - what - oh now wait a minute, 19 - 19 - 15 perhaps. Somewhere about then, 1915 or 16. The tea there, you - you got - salmon - nice helping of salmon, and - they'd bring 
some fruit on with custard. And - then they'd bring a cake and it was usually - either a cake that was - half of it had been taken or sometimes you got the full - cake, a real good sized cake and you could help yourself, take what you wanted, and the cost
 of that was one shilling each. Yes, so we did that - and then we'd walk - through the - fields, and through the - woods, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Clifton{\*\xmlclose}, come back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Clifton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And then from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Clifton{\*\xmlclose} we'd come over {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Clifton
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and walk home. Be quite a - a long walk, you see, it'd be a full afternoon and - getting on perhaps towards seven or eight at night when you got home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What about going to Colwick, this was when you were younger was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Ah this is when we were younger. We should have - we used to start out from home 
- then - I mostly used to go with the boys across the yard. And - we'd - have a bottle of tea, an ordinary pint bottle filled with tea and - milk and sugar in it you know, and we should take this with a few sandwiches and a string bag, and we should walk 
down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Colwick{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And - there - we used to - there was a refreshment stall - but - these boys knew the lady that was - in charge of it so we used to leave our bottles - there you see, and go and enjoy ourselves in the park. Well there there was a - a li
ttle bit of a zoo. And - then there was pie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 rots there. You see, well we should sit and watch the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 pierrots}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
, and then at odd times there was a - a fellow there with one leg named Gant - Gadsby, he used to climb up a great big pole onto a diving stage and dive in -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 With one leg?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Yes, and dive into the lake. Peggy Gadsby they called him. And - then of course there were the swings. Used to enjoy ourselves on the swings a little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 bit and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  then watch the steamers - come in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 front}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Trent{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and that. A
nd then - we should go back and have this - tea and sandwiches, of course the tea had got cold so we were drinking cold tea but that didn't matter those days. And then - after tea - when the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 pierrots}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  and everything had all finished we should - just - went away home again, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 At this stage were you swimming in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Trent{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes, it'd be about that time. It'd be about that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you have to pay to swim in the special place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No, it was free. It was - just a kind of a 
- iron shed put together, would it be about thirty or forty yards long, and there was a diving stage at the top end which went out - into the middle of the river, and the river at that time they used to say was about thirty foot deep. And then half way - 
in the - or shall I say in the middle of the bath, there was a diving stage that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 went}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 out to - a half way, quarter - quarter of the - width of the river where it was not quite so deep you see. And - some evenings we'd go. But mostly on a Sunday morning, we 
should get up at six o'clock - and - set off - down to the Trent, we should - go by way of Meadow Lane, down to the Trent. And then from the beg - beginning of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Trent
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} embankment, 'til we reached - the bath, we should trot down there. See? Get ourselves 
- warmed up you see, and limbered up, then we should go in, you'd - there were no cubicles or anything like that, you just - stripped down and your clothes would be left on the form, there - there - there wasn't much - in the way of - stealing or anything
 
like that, I never lost anything. And then we should perhaps run along the diving stage, dive into the centre of the river, and - in charge was a - fellow in charge of the bath and he had a boat - rowboat, so that if anyone got into difficulties he'd come
 
and fetch them out with a boat you see. And very often we should - dive in and swim right across the river, and on the other side there was a kind of a - a bit of a plantation, a few bushes and things like that you see, we used to sit in these bushes and 
- read, you'd take a paper across in your mouth you see, you see, and we should sit and read there and - the - bath attendant of course he'd be - shouting, come back, come back, you know, and we should come back at our leisure.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you go out in the evenings other than swimming?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Oh sometimes we'd go and play cricket, you know, for the - this - the - institute church institute and that. But it was not a regular - thing. None of this amusement, apart from going swimming on a Sunday morning, was a f
ixture. It'd be haphazard affair, you went just as you felt like it, you was making your own amusement - and you just went as you felt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you have any special friends at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Oh yes. Oh yes, I had a - a - a friend of mine, he got killed 
in the war. Which was very tragic really. We were good friends, for years and years and years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Was he the boy across the yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No. No. No, he was a boy that lived nearer down the Dale, you know, not quite to the - just by the church, but - his c
ondition of life was a lot different to mine. Although his parents were good parents. But - he - he had a different type of life, hit wasn't so hard for him you see. But - we proved real good - real good friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 You say you met new boys at work, did you meet any new girl friends at this time o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13508230\charrsid6829132 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  weren't you interested?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - just normal, I mean - we never went so far as to taking any of them out if that's what you mean. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you bring these friends home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 This - main friend that I had, I'll put it that way, oh yes, he used to come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did your parents or foster parents meet your friends apart from this special one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, not particularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did they expect to know where you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What each night? Oh yes, by gu
m yes. Up to - the age of - of starting to work. And then of course - I - no, after - when you - when you started to work you - you come - you'd gone from shall we say - a - a - a boy int a young man and you was allowed then to do - more or less what you 
liked, but - you had to be in at a certain time, there was no stopping out all hours that the Lord sent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What sort of time would it have been roughly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well, you - no later than ten, at the outside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 At this stage before 1918 did you take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well in a small way. In a small way. Not - I didn't - go in for politics as re as - as regards being a member of any political party, but - I was interested in what these different parties - stood for, I was gradually - learning
, shall we say to become a more responsible person. You see, this chap that used to work for my foster father, well he was - belonged the Labour party, a Socialist - well he told me about their doctrines, but it didn't alter me own opinion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 What did you think in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
Well I think I was more of a - a Liberal, a Conservative or Liberal at that time, but I didn't take - very kindly to the - Labour - side of things, until of course - you got older, and then of course when you joined the union 
when you went to work then you was - automatically thrown into the Labour field.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did this alter your views very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Well - it did a bit. It did a bit. You - you became more interested in whether a thing was - shall we say right - or whether th
ey - you were being twisted or - that's the simplest way of putting it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7429570 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 Did you vote in a general election before 1919, would you have been old enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10502885 JF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 No, I don't think so. No. And this machine never - showed any signs of coming back. So I took
 it into me own mind one day to go down to this Blackman's - shop - and I saw the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 Forman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 there, fellow named Starr. And - I told him who I was. I told him I was a discharged soldier and - this job had been promised to me when it came in, it was going to 
be in in a fortnight. So - he said, look my lad, come with me, he says, and I'll show you this machine, and when I got into the shop - at Blackman's - there was a heap of scrap as they'd taken it down from Morleys in the corner, it had never been touched.
 
Of course - I told him the circumstances, I'd been four years out of work, and he said, well - look my lad - he said, you've been abroad, he says, you've done plenty for us. These were his exact words, he says, I'll have that machine in Morleys in a fortn
i
ght's time. He said, you go back and tell Morleys it's coming in. No, I said, oh no. I said, you tell Morleys. You see. So he did. The - he went - he - notified Morleys it was coming in. So then of course - I went - in again in a fortnight's time and the 
machine had just come in. He had kept his word. He brought the machine in and - they got it going. Well then - I got at - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 started}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132  to work on this machine - and I'd been on it - oh I should think - two or three months, and then I broke down, I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12474664\charrsid6829132 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
, and - the nerves went a bit again, you know, and I had to stay at home under the doctor. Now - when - I did get better, and went back to work, I find out - that they'd set another young chap on this job. And this chap - played cricket for the firm in th
e
 - cricket - firm's cricket team you see. And - I couldn't get this job back, so I took it to the union. The union interviewed the firm, and I had to go back to - see the union committee by the week after, and then they told me that this - arrangement - w
ould - had been arranged for some time }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2705234\charrsid6829132 unbeknown}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10426719\charrsid6829132 
 to me you see. And - they agreed, the union agreed that this fellow should keep the job. So I was out of work again. And I can remember saying to the - secretary of the union - he'd just been made a Justice o
f the Peace, his name was Hartshorn, and I can remember saying to him then - well - if this is your idea of justice - then I hope to God I don't come before you on the bench. And that was that. And then I was out of work - I should think another month.

